ce:section.ce:para:
In our previous work, disulfide-bond-containing hyperbranched poly(amido amine) (HPAP) end-capped with polyethylenimine (PEI, 600 Da) was developed (Scheme 1
                     A) and exhibited positive charge and glutathione (GSH)-responsive [24]. Herein, we introduced the HPAP as precursor to prepare carbonized polymer dots (CPDs) through one-pot microwave-assisted treatment, accomplishing synchronous preparation, passivation and functionalization. The obtained CPDs were endowed with extra considerable fluorescent quantum yield and high specific surface area as the rapamycin carrier apart from the original property of HPAP. In addition, the rapamycin-loaded CPDs as the core was further assembled with a cleavable shell of dimethylmaleic acid modified mPEG-PEI600 copolymer which displayed microenvironment-triggered charge reversal and size shrinkage (Scheme 1B&C). This core/shell structured CPDs-based rapamycin delivery system exhibited cascaded responsiveness responding to blood-tissue-cells multistage biological barriers (Scheme 2
                     ). Once systemic administration, the non-specific interaction with blood components could be avoided benefitting from the PEGylated shell; when permeating through tumor tissue, acidic tumor microenvironment induced PEG de-shielding and thereby elicited charge reversal and size shrinkage, facilitating tumor accumulation; after being endocytosed by tumor cell, GSH-triggered degradation of HPAP boosts the drug release into cytosol. Accordingly, this CPDs-based multifunctional theranostic platform with cascaded responsiveness remarkably enhances the permeability and retention at tumor sites for precise rapamycin delivery, as well as synchronously assisted with imaging tracking.
